The paper deals with the problem of setting prices for potential buyers with unknown valuations drawn from an unknown distribution, which is a common problem in auction theory. The paper uses tools from differential privacy and information theory, which are commonly used in the sub-categories of cs.GT (game theory) and cs.IT (information theory). The paper also discusses sample complexity bounds, which are relevant to the sub-category of cs.DS (data structures and algorithms). Additionally, the paper proposes pricing strategies that optimize expected revenue, which is a common problem in the sub-categories of cs.LG (machine learning) and cs.AI (artificial intelligence).
